        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13240",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "After a quick review, it seems like the place where code meets the database is always in:\n\nline 132~ish of Zend\/Db\/Adapter\/Abstract.php -- \n\n    \/**\n     * Special handling for PDO query().\n     * All bind parameter names must begin with ':'\n     *\n     * @param string|Zend_Db_Select $sql The SQL statement with placeholders.\n     * @param array $bind An array of data to bind to the placeholders.\n     * @return Zend_Db_Pdo_Statement\n     *\/\n    public function query($sql, $bind = array())\n    {\n        if (is_array($bind)) {\n            foreach ($bind as $name => $value) {\n                if (!is_int($name) && !preg_match('\/^:\/', $name)) {\n                    $newName = \":$name\";\n                    unset($bind[$name]);\n                    $bind[$newName] = $value;\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        return parent::query($sql, $bind);\n    }\n\n\n\nPerhaps for granularity, all adapters should at the very least implement a query() that forwards the request to parent::query() and if errors occur, they should produce their own adapter flavored exception.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-09T13:29:54.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-09T13:29:54.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13241",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks for the help!  I see where this needs to happen.\n\nAs for granular exceptions, we don't currently have distinct exceptions for the diffrent PDO adapters.  We only have distinct exceptions for non-PDO adapters (though I question why this is useful).  So I would just re-throw a Zend_Db_Adapter_Exception if we get a PDOException.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-09T14:16:57.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-09T14:16:57.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13243",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thats fine, i saw that Db2\/Exception existed, as did ORacle\/Exception.php\n\nThe only reason i thought there might be a need for granular exceptions is so that if an exception had funky default messages (like the PDO [SQLSTATE]... prefix), a more friendly message could propagate down the stack to the caught DB\/Exception.php type.. IE, there would be no more [SQLSTATE] #### stuff in the final caught Zend_Db_Exception::getMessage() output.\n\njust some thoughts..\n\n-ralph",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-09T14:31:33.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-09T14:31:33.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13244",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I plan to use a backend-neutral exception message, and \"chain\" the PDOException.  \n\nCf. Zend_Gdata_HttpException.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-09T14:46:16.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-09T14:46:16.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13246",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "That sounds like a winner.\nThanks,\nRalph",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=ralph",
                        "name": "ralph",
                        "displayName": "Ralph Schindler",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-09T14:57:25.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-09T14:57:25.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13356",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Set component to Zend_Db.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-15T12:30:05.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-15T12:30:05.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13654",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "As of revision 4202, the PDOException is now re-thrown as a Zend_Db_Adapter_Exception.  The original PDOException is added to the new exception in a \"chained\" fashion, and is accessible via a method \"getChainedException()\".",
